    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Is the contrast injection painful?",
        "answer": "Most patients feel only a cool sensation; mild bruising can occur at the IV site.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "How long does the scan take?",
        "answer": "30–45 minutes total, including positioning and contrast wait time.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Can I drive after the scan?",
        "answer": "Yes, unless you received sedatives—then arrange a companion.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "What if I’m claustrophobic?",
        "answer": "Open-bore MRI, music headsets, or mild sedation are available.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Are there alternatives to contrast?",
        "answer": "Non-contrast high-field MRI or CT myelography exist, but they may miss subtle lesions.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Do I need to fast before an MRI of the neck and upper back with contrast?",
        "answer": "Generally, fasting (not eating or drinking) is not required before an **MRI Cervical/Cervico-Dorsal Spine with Contrast** if you are not scheduled to receive any form of sedation. You can usually eat, drink, and take your medications as normal. However, if sedation is planned as part of your procedure (e.g., for claustrophobia), you will receive specific fasting instructions. It's always best to confirm any specific preparation instructions with the Cadabams Diagnostics staff when scheduling your appointment or during any pre-procedure calls."
      }
    ],
